the desolate prospect,

271
00:25:10,839 --> 00:25:13,865
its blackness recalling
the Sea of the Dead.

272
00:25:42,271 --> 00:25:44,501
Are we outside the city limits?

273
00:25:45,074 --> 00:25:47,804
I've never really known.

274
00:25:48,343 --> 00:25:50,743
They once called it
the Isle of Ravens.

275
00:25:51,413 --> 00:25:52,880
Not staying in the car?

276
00:25:53,048 --> 00:25:55,608
We'll find some quiet place to talk.

277
00:25:56,785 --> 00:26:00,277
I'll take a bus back. I have practice.

278
00:26:00,489 --> 00:26:04,050
I'll see if Madame Victoria's in.
I'll go back with you.

279
00:26:04,593 --> 00:26:06,754
Then I'll stay since she's going.

280
00:26:07,029 --> 00:26:08,929
But I'll be back, I said.

281
00:26:11,333 --> 00:26:13,927
It won't be your first lie.

282
00:26:15,971 --> 00:26:17,768
Not at all.

283
00:26:18,440 --> 00:26:21,000
I'll say I'm going shopping.

284
00:26:23,445 --> 00:26:25,072
Who lives in the house?

285
00:26:25,314 --> 00:26:27,976
- At the villa, you mean?
- Where else?

286
00:26:29,251 --> 00:26:31,276
There's Mr. Stolz.

287
00:26:31,620 --> 00:26:34,384
He's there sometimes
but I've never seen him.

288
00:26:34,890 --> 00:26:38,849
Then there's Madame Victoria and me,
plus the gardener.

289
00:26:40,429 --> 00:26:42,090
He around a lot?

290
00:26:42,631 --> 00:26:44,462
I don't know.

291
00:26:45,134 --> 00:26:46,965
He ever try to paw you?

292
00:26:47,169 --> 00:26:50,138
You're nuts! He's very well-behaved.

293
00:26:50,339 --> 00:26:51,806
So you have seen him.

294
00:26:51,907 --> 00:26:54,705
- Is the money his or hers?
- It's not hers.

295
00:26:54,943 --> 00:26:58,435
- Why does he hide it?
- I don't know.

296
00:27:00,015 --> 00:27:01,812
I don't know.

297
00:27:02,451 --> 00:27:05,113
Maybe he's cheating on his taxes.

298
00:27:07,022 --> 00:27:09,081
You got me all wrong.

299
00:27:09,291 --> 00:27:12,556
He robs the government
and deserves to be robbed himself.

300
00:27:14,696 --> 00:27:17,722
So will you wait? I'll be back.

301
00:27:18,867 --> 00:27:21,335
Okay. We'll wait behind the factory.

302
00:27:21,570 --> 00:27:23,333
Okay.

303
00:27:29,711 --> 00:27:31,941
The girl's an idiot!

304
00:28:20,062 --> 00:28:21,996
Aunt Victoria!

305
00:28:31,940 --> 00:28:33,532
I'm here.

306
00:28:51,360 --> 00:28:56,320
You'll never win at Indianapolis!
Never!

307
00:28:57,199 --> 00:28:58,826
Got that?

308
00:28:59,534 --> 00:29:01,900
You'll never win, I tell you!

309
00:30:03,298 --> 00:30:05,163
Odile!

310
00:30:25,153 --> 00:30:28,611
- I'll win!
- It's me, Odile and South America!

311
00:30:28,824 --> 00:30:32,191
- Here I am.
- Is Mr. Stolz's driver here?

312
00:30:32,361 --> 00:30:36,127
- No one's around.
- What a nuisance. He's always late.

313
00:30:54,383 --> 00:30:58,080
No answer. One of these days
the boss will have a fit.

314
00:30:59,020 --> 00:31:00,612
What boss?

315
00:31:00,722 --> 00:31:02,280
Mr. Stolz?

316
00:31:02,491 --> 00:31:04,049
Still seeing that boy?

317
00:31:04,259 --> 00:31:05,920
What boy?

318
00:31:06,395 --> 00:31:07,953
Franz?

319
00:31:08,096 --> 00:31:10,087
No, he dropped the course.

320
00:31:10,332 --> 00:31:14,063
He says England's done for
and it's the Chinese who'll win.

321
00:31:14,636 --> 00:31:16,467
So he's studying Chinese.

322
00:31:16,671 --> 00:31:20,232
Someday I'll check
that you're not going to the movies.

323
00:31:20,342 --> 00:31:21,639
I hate movies.

324
00:31:21,743 --> 00:31:24,211
- The theater, then.
- I hate theater.

325
00:31:24,446 --> 00:31:28,246
- Or dancing at Mimi Pinson's.
- I hate that, too.

326
00:31:28,483 --> 00:31:30,348
Or strolling on the boulevards.

327
00:31:30,585 --> 00:31:32,109
I hate the boulevards.

328
00:31:32,320 --> 00:31:34,481
What do you love, then?

329
00:31:34,723 --> 00:31:36,281
I don't know.

330
00:31:37,426 --> 00:31:39,360
I love nature.

331
00:31:42,464 --> 00:31:44,091
Where are you going?

332
00:31:44,199 --> 00:31:46,963
To a reception at the Albanian Embassy.

333
00:31:53,775 --> 00:31:56,869
I'm taking 1,000 francs
to do some shopping.

334
00:31:56,978 --> 00:31:58,946
1,000 francs...

335
00:32:30,545 --> 00:32:33,105
Been in Mr. Stolz's room
today or yesterday?

336
00:32:33,415 --> 00:32:36,680
Me? I never go in there.

337
00:32:38,353 --> 00:32:40,014
How strange.

338
00:32:40,121 --> 00:32:43,750
Something's out of place.
I missed it this morning.

339
00:32:44,459 --> 00:32:46,950
Maybe he moved the furniture around.

340
00:32:47,162 --> 00:32:48,925
Not at all.

341
00:32:50,565 --> 00:32:53,500
Did he say he wanted his coat cleaned?

342
00:32:56,004 --> 00:32:59,235
That must be it. He forget to tell us.

343
00:33:08,350 --> 00:33:10,079
I'll ask him about it.

344
00:33:10,285 --> 00:33:12,651
Have a nice evening. I'm off.

345
00:33:47,923 --> 00:33:50,585
"Tragedy of Disappointed Love!

346
00:33:51,359 --> 00:33:55,819
Myriam, 21, stabs her artist lover

347
00:33:56,264 --> 00:33:58,858
in his studio in southern Paris.

348
00:33:59,200 --> 00:34:02,328
He'd wanted to be alone."

349
00:34:03,605 --> 00:34:07,632
"Orleans -A third man holds
the key to the killings.

350
00:34:08,643 --> 00:34:11,544
He'd received a package
from Jacqueline,

351
00:34:11,780 --> 00:34:14,374
who was later found dead
with her baby.

352
00:34:14,950 --> 00:34:18,647
He was seen driving a black Chevrolet."

353
00:34:34,569 --> 00:34:37,402
"'She treated me like a servant,'
said the lumberjack,

354
00:34:37,505 --> 00:34:40,497
husband of the missing chatelaine.

355
00:34:40,609 --> 00:34:42,941
Murder, say the police.

356
00:34:43,178 --> 00:34:45,339
But Roger claims she ran away.

357
00:34:46,147 --> 00:34:49,412
In slippers... A fruitless search..."

358
00:34:49,517 --> 00:34:53,283
"'I hate you,' the fiendish Huguette
told her lover

359
00:34:53,521 --> 00:34:56,854
in the car that led
to the killers' arrest.

360
00:34:58,026 --> 00:35:01,291
She couldn't forgive his flirting..."

361
00:35:01,496 --> 00:35:03,862
"He prepared breakfast
for his wife and daughters

362
00:35:04,065 --> 00:35:06,761
before killing them,
then taking his own life."

363
00:35:08,136 --> 00:35:10,070
Rajah!

364
00:35:14,776 --> 00:35:16,505
Hello, boy!

365
00:35:19,814 --> 00:35:21,543
No appetite?

366
00:35:21,783 --> 00:35:23,512
Don't want it?

367
00:35:33,995 --> 00:35:35,519
"From our correspondent:

368
00:35:35,630 --> 00:35:39,225
Unimaginable massacres in East Africa.

369
00:35:40,335 --> 00:35:44,669
Hutus have sawed off the legs
of giant Tutsis, their former masters,

370
00:35:44,939 --> 00:35:47,499
to bring them down to size.

371
00:35:48,276 --> 00:35:52,713
Rwanda's rivers are choked
with the bodies of 20,000 victims.

372
00:35:53,248 --> 00:35:56,740
The king, 7'2" tall,
has fled the country.

373
00:35:57,752 --> 00:36:00,880
Peking supports the kingdom of giants."

374
00:36:46,735 --> 00:36:48,202
Franz!

375
00:36:51,439 --> 00:36:53,999
- Over here!
- How much money did she say?

376
00:36:54,242 --> 00:36:57,973
A big pile, she said.
Maybe 40 or 50 wads of bills.

377
00:36:58,179 --> 00:37:00,147
Could be 200 million.

378
00:37:00,381 --> 00:37:02,975
Still, I wonder why she told me.

379
00:37:03,118 --> 00:37:05,348
She's not all there.

380
00:37:08,490 --> 00:37:10,287
Why call Franz and not me?

381
00:37:10,492 --> 00:37:13,620
It's dumb, but I forgot your name.

382
00:37:13,962 --> 00:37:15,589
Is it Alfred or Arthur?

383
00:37:16,765 --> 00:37:20,201
Drive me to Vincennes.
It's cold. I'll take the Metro.

384
00:37:20,401 --> 00:37:22,528
Good idea.
We'll work out a plan in a café.

385
00:37:22,737 --> 00:37:24,637
Why a plan?

386
00:37:28,910 --> 00:37:32,402
A thought crossed Odile's mind
like a dark cloud:

387
00:37:32,514 --> 00:37:34,914
Arthur would always look at her

388
00:37:35,150 --> 00:37:38,244
like a shadow masking his view,

389
00:37:38,520 --> 00:37:42,923
as if an ocean of indifference
lay between them.

390
00:39:09,744 --> 00:39:12,144
- You having what?
- A Coca-Cola.

391
00:39:12,513 --> 00:39:16,574
"You-hav-ing-what? Co-ca-Co-la."
It doesn't rhyme.

392
00:39:16,784 --> 00:39:19,014
I'll have a peppermint soda.

393
00:39:19,120 --> 00:39:21,111
A schnapps and a Coca-Cola.

394
00:39:21,322 --> 00:39:23,552
And a peppermint soda!

395
00:39:31,766 --> 00:39:34,633
You seem to be having dark thoughts.

396
00:39:34,769 --> 00:39:36,634
You said it.

397
00:39:38,539 --> 00:39:40,837
Well, I saw it.

398
00:39:41,075 --> 00:39:43,168
- Saw what?
- The money.

399
00:39:43,912 --> 00:39:47,313
When I first told you about it,
I hadn't seen it.

400
00:39:48,082 --> 00:39:51,711
But now I have.
There's too much. I'm scared.

401
00:39:52,220 --> 00:39:54,051
So this time, it's for real.

402
00:39:54,389 --> 00:39:58,018
Why did you tell him?
That was a lousy thing to do.

403
00:40:00,828 --> 00:40:02,455
Got 20 francs?

404
00:40:02,764 --> 00:40:04,493
Give.

405
00:40:12,640 --> 00:40:14,972
He guessed it.
I didn't say a thing.

406
00:40:16,744 --> 00:40:19,804
This isn't your first lie either.

407
00:40:20,548 --> 00:40:23,608
He tell you he killed
his grandma with a hammer?

408
00:40:23,851 --> 00:40:26,945
- Really?
- No. Second lie.

409
00:40:28,022 --> 00:40:30,923
- Why'd you say that?
- To scare you.

410
00:40:55,083 --> 00:40:57,017
There's a run in your stocking.

411
00:41:01,522 --> 00:41:03,456
No, there isn't.

412
00:41:11,099 --> 00:41:12,964
What were you two saying?

413
00:41:13,534 --> 00:41:16,059
Just talking about the weather.

414
00:41:19,607 --> 00:41:22,235
- Tell me where his room is.
- Whose room?

415
00:41:22,610 --> 00:41:24,339
Mr. Stolz.

416
00:41:27,015 --> 00:41:29,916
So where is it?
On the second floor?

417
00:41:30,151 --> 00:41:32,381
Does he lock the door?

418
00:41:32,887 --> 00:41:35,117
But I'm not allowed to go in.

419
00:41:37,225 --> 00:41:39,250
- How much is there?
- I don't know.

420
00:41:39,494 --> 00:41:41,462
I told you already.

421
00:41:42,530 --> 00:41:44,498
Don't be afraid.

422
00:41:44,799 --> 00:41:46,664
You should've counted it.

423
00:41:46,968 --> 00:41:49,266
Think big.
- I don't want to.

424
00:41:49,504 --> 00:41:51,631
Then you shouldn't have told us.

425
00:41:52,640 --> 00:41:54,608
You're a drag.

426
00:41:55,176 --> 00:41:57,076
You're our accomplice now.

427
00:42:02,283 --> 00:42:04,148
Don't cry.

428
00:42:08,890 --> 00:42:11,120
Now that we love each other,

429
00:42:11,592 --> 00:42:13,719
everything will be fine.

430
00:42:13,961 --> 00:42:15,758
Franz will help us.

431
00:42:16,297 --> 00:42:18,891
Better to be rich and happy
than poor and unhappy.

432
00:42:22,370 --> 00:42:24,838
- We could do it tonight?
- Not tonight.

433
00:42:25,206 --> 00:42:27,140
Mr. Stolz should be back.

434
00:42:27,842 --> 00:42:29,241
Tomorrow.

435
00:42:29,377 --> 00:42:32,278
He has a reception.
Tomorrow or the day after.

436
00:42:32,847 --> 00:42:35,179
It's the day after, I think, yes.

437
00:42:36,384 --> 00:42:37,976
Is it yes or no?

438
00:42:42,757 --> 00:42:45,282
Day after tomorrow, then.

439
00:42:45,726 --> 00:42:47,489
Be right back.

440
00:42:59,407 --> 00:43:01,398
Strange that his room's unlocked.

441
00:43:01,609 --> 00:43:02,906
Not at all.

442
00:43:03,077 --> 00:43:06,911
Sometimes things are best hidden
in full view of everyone.

443
00:43:07,315 --> 00:43:10,148
I read an American book
where that happened.

444
00:43:10,551 --> 00:43:13,042
The police were looking for a letter.

445
00:43:13,254 --> 00:43:15,950
The thief left it lying on the table.

446
00:43:41,249 --> 00:43:44,241
KEEP YOURYOUTHFUL EYES

447
00:43:50,057 --> 00:43:54,118
"It's not only your looks,
but your happiness, too.

448
00:43:54,362 --> 00:43:56,592
Good eye care depends on you."

449
00:44:01,836 --> 00:44:03,895
- Hurry up.
- Get lost.

450
00:44:10,111 --> 00:44:11,601
Join us, miss?

451
00:44:11,712 --> 00:44:14,010
- Got connections at Renault?
- No, why?

452
00:44:14,215 --> 00:44:18,242
Too bad. You could've traded in
your dumb looks for a car.

453
00:44:41,175 --> 00:44:42,802
So what do we do now?

454
00:44:42,910 --> 00:44:44,502
What do we do?

455
00:44:45,079 --> 00:44:46,376
I don't know.

456
00:44:46,480 --> 00:44:49,711
Or rather, I say I don't know,
but I do know.

457
00:44:54,555 --> 00:44:57,547
Hand me that thing in my coat.

458
00:44:58,459 --> 00:45:00,859
In the pocket.

459
00:45:01,596 --> 00:45:02,995
This?

460
00:45:05,233 --> 00:45:06,791
Look.

461
00:45:08,536 --> 00:45:11,061
Put your hand around the ball.

462
00:45:15,409 --> 00:45:17,240
Nothing's happening.

463
00:45:18,112 --> 00:45:20,979
The liquid should flow
to the other side.

464
00:45:27,855 --> 00:45:29,322
Okay.

465
00:45:29,523 --> 00:45:33,050
If there's nothing to say,
let's have a minute of silence.

466
00:45:33,494 --> 00:45:35,826
You can really be dumb sometimes.

467
00:45:37,565 --> 00:45:40,033
A minute of silence
can be a long time.

468
00:45:41,235 --> 00:45:44,261
A real minute of silence
takes forever.

469
00:45:44,772 --> 00:45:47,332
Okay. One, two, three...

470
00:46:23,210 --> 00:46:27,510
That's enough.
I'll put a record on.

471
00:46:33,521 --> 00:46:37,013
Why is Franz staying?
Does he go everywhere with you?

472
00:46:40,394 --> 00:46:42,988
In case anyone takes a shot at you.

473
00:46:43,097 --> 00:46:46,362
It's like in the movies.
He'd make a good shield.

474
00:46:46,901 --> 00:46:49,028
What a horrible thing to say.

475
00:46:55,076 --> 00:46:56,509
Shall we dance?

476
00:46:56,744 --> 00:46:58,473
Sure. What?

477
00:46:59,980 --> 00:47:01,811
No, I prefer this.

478
00:47:04,352 --> 00:47:06,183
Okay, let's go.

479
00:47:12,993 --> 00:47:17,828
Empires crumble, republics founder.

480
00:47:17,932 --> 00:47:21,424
But fools go on.
- Bravo, Mr. Segalot. That's real furniture!

481
00:48:09,517 --> 00:48:12,179
Now is the time for a digression

482
00:48:12,319 --> 00:48:14,412
in which to describe
our heroes'feelings.

483
00:48:31,639 --> 00:48:33,470
Arthur keeps watching his feet,

484
00:48:33,707 --> 00:48:36,835
but his mind's on Odile's mouth
and her romantic kisses.

485
00:48:53,294 --> 00:48:55,421
Odile is wondering if the boys notice

486
00:48:55,663 --> 00:48:58,632
her breasts moving under her sweater.

487
00:49:13,414 --> 00:49:15,382
Franz thinks of everything and nothing.

488
00:49:15,850 --> 00:49:18,751
He wonders if the world
is becoming a dream

489
00:49:19,053 --> 00:49:21,419
or if the dream
is becoming the world.

490
00:50:52,313 --> 00:50:55,373
Arthur tossed a coin
to see who'd get Odile.

491
00:50:55,583 --> 00:50:56,948
He called heads.

492
00:50:57,051 --> 00:50:59,918
Odile yelled heads,
the coin showed tails.

493
00:51:00,154 --> 00:51:05,057
Franz took the car and drove around,
sad and lonely, his gaze feverish.

494
00:51:05,259 --> 00:51:08,285
Meanwhile, on the city outskirts,
Arthur told Odile

495
00:51:08,395 --> 00:51:11,262
how he once met a fellow
who walked this way...

496
00:51:28,015 --> 00:51:30,483
What's your family name, Arthur?

497
00:51:30,985 --> 00:51:32,384
Rimbaud.

498
00:51:32,686 --> 00:51:34,119
Like my father.

499
00:51:34,588 --> 00:51:37,921
That little old man
who was spying on us?

500
00:51:39,460 --> 00:51:42,122
That's my uncle. My father's dead.

501
00:51:43,097 --> 00:51:45,759
How much is the Mauser?
- Two francs.

502
00:51:55,376 --> 00:51:57,344
How would you feel if a live man

503
00:51:57,444 --> 00:52:00,413
was in your sights, like in battle?

504
00:52:02,449 --> 00:52:05,009
I feel that if there was one,

505
00:52:05,119 --> 00:52:07,610
right now he'd be dead.

506
00:52:09,990 --> 00:52:11,423
Let's go home.

507
00:52:11,592 --> 00:52:14,425
Don't take advantage of me.
I love you.

508
00:52:14,628 --> 00:52:16,095
Can I have my target?

509
00:52:16,263 --> 00:52:19,357
Already?
- Lightning struck.

510
00:52:26,540 --> 00:52:29,532
Arthur said such love talk was crap.

511
00:52:29,910 --> 00:52:32,674
Odile said she'd blurted it out
but meant it.

512
00:52:33,147 --> 00:52:35,445
Then they walked down to Place Clichy,

513
00:52:35,883 --> 00:52:39,614
one of the loveliest squares at night.

514
00:52:40,487 --> 00:52:43,422
It brought them back
to the present, the past,

515
00:52:44,058 --> 00:52:46,322
and their intrepid future.

516
00:52:52,366 --> 00:52:55,858
Whereupon they went down
into the center of the earth.

517
00:53:42,549 --> 00:53:44,710
You change girlfriends often?

518
00:53:47,287 --> 00:53:48,982
What makes you say that?

519
00:53:49,690 --> 00:53:53,854
Franz said you had
a different girl every day.

520
00:54:09,643 --> 00:54:11,668
What do you see in me?

521
00:54:12,846 --> 00:54:14,871
And you in me?

522
00:54:19,386 --> 00:54:21,047
I don't know.

523
00:54:22,422 --> 00:54:24,481
A husband.

524
00:54:33,233 --> 00:54:35,531
Is that what interests you?

525
00:54:43,677 --> 00:54:46,202
What exactly does it mean to you?

526
00:54:51,518 --> 00:54:55,477
It means offering your breasts
and your thighs.

527
00:55:06,133 --> 00:55:10,467
People in the Metro
always look so sad and lonely.

528
00:55:14,808 --> 00:55:17,709
Look at that one.
Why that expression?

